{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4e7d8400-fb5f-4238-9dc3-9807272fe1f2","content":"No worries — here's how to configure it. Create a `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`command`/`args`** — runs `dotnet run` pointing at your project.\n- Your server must use **stdio transport** (not HTTP/SSE). If you're using the `ModelContextProtocol` NuGet package, ensure you call `.WithStdioServerTransport()` in your builder.\n\nAfter saving, open the **MCP panel** in VS Code (command palette → \"MCP: List Servers\") to verify the server starts and its tools are discovered.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3fc2d439-4511-4f26-aaad-cb6258879fe0","outputTokens":249,"requestId":"F3D4:184190:11606E:15B478:69F54E1B"},"id":"2700bdf3-430b-4b5a-8bf4-dd309c4c066c","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:06:44.090Z","parentId":"79dd1f6b-dc93-410f-8a53-79281360753d"}
